UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 AN ACT relating to interscholastic athletics.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 156.070 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) The Kentucky Board of Education shall have the management and control of the
5 common schools and all programs operated in these schools, including
6 interscholastic athletics, the Kentucky School for the Deaf, the Kentucky School for
7 the Blind, and community education programs and services.
8 (2) The Kentucky Board of Education may designate an organization or agency to
9 manage interscholastic athletics in the common schools, provided that the rules,
10 regulations, and bylaws of any organization or agency so designated shall be
11 approved by the board, and provided further that any administrative hearing
12 conducted by the designated managing organization or agency shall be conducted in
13 accordance with KRS Chapter 13B.
14 (a) The state board or its designated agency shall assure through promulgation of
15 administrative regulations that if a secondary school sponsors or intends to
16 sponsor an athletic activity or sport that is similar to a sport for which
17 National Collegiate Athletic Association members offer an athletic
18 scholarship, the school shall sponsor the athletic activity or sport for which a
19 scholarship is offered. The administrative regulations shall specify which
20 athletic activities are similar to sports for which National Collegiate Athletic
21 Association members offer scholarships.
22 (b) Beginning with the 2003-2004 school year, the state board shall require any
23 agency or organization designated by the state board to manage interscholastic
24 athletics to adopt bylaws that establish as members of the agency's or
25 organization's board of control one (1) representative of nonpublic member
26 schools who is elected by the nonpublic school members of the agency or
27 organization from regions one (1) through eight (8) and one (1) representative
Page 1 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 of nonpublic member schools who is elected by the nonpublic member
2 schools of the agency or organization from regions nine (9) through sixteen
3 (16). The nonpublic school representatives on the board of control shall not be
4 from classification A1 or D1 schools. Following initial election of these
5 nonpublic school representatives to the agency's or organization's board of
6 control, terms of the nonpublic school representatives shall be staggered so
7 that only one (1) nonpublic school member is elected in each even-numbered
8 year.
9 (c) The state board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
10 interscholastic athletics shall not promulgate rules, administrative regulations,
11 or by laws that prohibit pupils in grades seven (7) to eight (8) from
12 participating in any high school sports except for high school varsity soccer,
13 football, and boys or coed lacrosse, or from participating on more than one (1)
14 school-sponsored team at the same time in the same sport. The Kentucky
15 Board of Education, or an agency designated by the board to manage
16 interscholastic athletics, may promulgate administrative regulations
17 restricting, limiting, or prohibiting participation in high school varsity soccer
18 and football for students who have not successfully completed the eighth
19 grade.
20 (d) 1. The state board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
21 interscholastic athletics shall allow a member school's team or students
22 to play against students of a nonmember at-home private school, or a
23 team of students from nonmember at-home private schools, if the
24 nonmember at-home private schools and students comply with this
25 subsection.
26 2. A nonmember at-home private school's team and students shall comply
27 with the rules for student-athletes, including rules concerning:
Page 2 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 a. Age;
2 b. School semesters;
3 c. Scholarships;
4 d. Physical exams;
5 e. Foreign student eligibility; and
6 f. Amateurs.
7 3. A coach of a nonmember at-home private school's team shall comply
8 with the rules concerning certification of member school coaches as
9 required by the state board or any agency designated by the state board
10 to manage interscholastic athletics.
11 4. This subsection shall not allow a nonmember at-home private school's
12 team to participate in a sanctioned:
13 a. Conference;
14 b. Conference tournament;
15 c. District tournament;
16 d. Regional tournament; or
17 e. State tournament or event.
18 5. This subsection does not allow eligibility for a recognition, award, or
19 championship sponsored by the state board or any agency designated by
20 the state board to manage interscholastic athletics.
21 6. A nonmember at-home private school's team or students may participate
22 in interscholastic athletics permitted, offered, or sponsored by the state
23 board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
24 interscholastic athletics.
25 (e) 1. Every local board of education shall require an annual medical
26 examination performed and signed by a physician, physician assistant,
27 advanced practice registered nurse, or chiropractor, if performed within
Page 3 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 the professional's scope of practice, for each student seeking eligibility
2 to participate in any school athletic activity or sport.
3 2. Any interscholastic athletics participation consent form that is adopted
4 by the Kentucky Board of Education or any organization or agency
5 designated by the state board to manage interscholastic athletics shall
6 include the following information:
7 a. A student-athlete may report instances of child dependency,
8 neglect, and abuse to any adult;
9 b. Any person who knows or has reasonable cause to believe that a
10 child is dependent, neglected, or abused shall report that
11 information pursuant to KRS 620.030; and
12 c. References to instructions on reporting child dependency, neglect,
13 and abuse, including KRS 620.030.
14 3. The Kentucky Board of Education or any organization or agency
15 designated by the state board to manage interscholastic athletics shall
16 include the following information in any training for administrators and
17 coaches under its jurisdiction:
18 a. The duty to report instances of child dependency, neglect, and
19 abuse;[ and]
20 b. Procedures for reporting child dependency, neglect, and abuse
21 under KRS 620.030; and
22 c. How to prevent suicide through the identification of risk factors
23 and warning signs along with other high-quality, evidence-based
24 information for the prevention of suicide.
25 4. The Kentucky Board of Education or any organization or agency
26 designated by the state board to manage interscholastic athletics shall
27 not promulgate administrative regulations or adopt any policies or
Page 4 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 bylaws that are contrary to the provisions of this paragraph.
2 (f) Any student who turns nineteen (19) years of age prior to August 1 shall not
3 be eligible for high school athletics in Kentucky. Any student who turns
4 nineteen (19) years of age on or after August 1 shall remain eligible for that
5 school year only. An exception to the provisions of this paragraph shall be
6 made, and the student shall be eligible for high school athletics in Kentucky if
7 the student:
8 1. Qualified for exceptional children services and had an individual
9 education program developed by an admissions and release committee
10 (ARC) while the student was enrolled in the primary school program;
11 2. Was retained in the primary school program because of an ARC
12 committee recommendation; and
13 3. Has not completed four (4) consecutive years or eight (8) consecutive
14 semesters of eligibility following initial promotion from grade eight (8)
15 to grade nine (9).
16 (g) The state board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
17 interscholastic athletics shall promulgate administrative regulations or bylaws
18 that provide that:
19 1. A member school shall designate all athletic teams, activities, and sports
20 for students in grades six (6) through twelve (12) as one (1) of the
21 following categories:
22 a. "Boys";
23 b. "Coed"; or
24 c. "Girls";
25 2. The sex of a student for the purpose of determining eligibility to
26 participate in an athletic activity or sport shall be determined by:
27 a. A student's biological sex as indicated on the student's original,
Page 5 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 unedited birth certificate issued at the time of birth; or
2 b. An affidavit signed and sworn to by the physician, physician
3 assistant, advanced practice registered nurse, or chiropractor that
4 conducted the annual medical examination required by paragraph
5 (e) of this subsection under penalty of perjury establishing the
6 student's biological sex at the time of birth;
7 3. a. An athletic activity or sport designated as "girls" for students in
8 grades six (6) through twelve (12) shall not be open to members of
9 the male sex.
10 b. Nothing in this section shall be construed to restrict the eligibility
11 of any student to participate in an athletic activity or sport
12 designated as "boys" or "coed"; and
13 4. Neither the state board, any agency designated by the state board to
14 manage interscholastic athletics, any school district, nor any member
15 school shall entertain a complaint, open an investigation, or take any
16 other adverse action against a school for maintaining separate
17 interscholastic or intramural athletic teams, activities, or sports for
18 students of the female sex.
19 (h) 1. The state board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
20 interscholastic athletics shall promulgate administrative regulations that
21 permit a school district to employ or assign nonteaching or noncertified
22 personnel or personnel without postsecondary education credit hours to
23 serve in a coaching position. The administrative regulations shall give
24 preference to the hiring or assignment of certified personnel in coaching
25 positions.
26 2. A person employed in a coaching position shall be a high school
27 graduate and at least twenty-one (21) years of age and shall submit to a
Page 6 of 10
XXXX 2/25/2026 9:16 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1844
1 criminal background check in accordance with KRS 160.380.
2 3. The administrative regulations shall specify post-hire requirements for
3 persons employed in coaching positions.
4 4. The regulations shall permit a predetermined number of hours of
5 professional development training approved by the state board or its
6 designated agency to be used in lieu of postsecondary education credit
7 hour requirements.
8 5. A local school board may specify post-hire requirements for personnel
9 employed in coaching positions in addition to those specified in
10 subparagraph 3. of this paragraph.
11 (i) Unless permitted to be eligible for varsity athletics by any transfer rule,
12 policy, or administrative regulation promulgated by the state board or any
13 agency designated by the state board to manage interscholastic athletics, any
14 student who transfers enrollment from a district of residence to a nonresident
15 district under KRS 157.350(4)(b) after enrolling in grade nine (9) and
16 participating in a varsity sport shall be ineligible to participate in
17 interscholastic athletics for one (1) calendar year from the date of the transfer.
18 The state board or any agency designated by the state board to manage
19 interscholastic athletics may adopt rules, policies, and bylaws and promulgate
20 administrative regulations necessary to carry out this paragraph.
21 (j) No member school shall grant a student-athlete the right to use the member
22 school's property, or intellectual property, such as trademarks, school
23 uniforms, and copyrights, in the student's earning of compensation through
24 name, image, and likeness activities. No student-athlete shall use school
25 property or such intellectual property in earning compensation through name,
26 image, and likeness activities. The state board or any agency designated by
27 the state board to manage interscholastic athletics shall promulgate
Page 7 of 10
